# Project Coding Conventions (LEGACY)
#
# NOTE: This is the legacy .cursorrules format. Prefer using .cursor/rules/*.mdc
# files for new rules. This file is kept for backward compatibility.

## General

- Use TypeScript strict mode in all files
- Prefer `const` over `let`; never use `var`
- Use named exports over default exports
- Keep functions under 30 lines; extract helpers when complexity grows
- Write JSDoc comments for all public functions and interfaces

## TypeScript

- Enable strict null checks — handle `null` and `undefined` explicitly
- Use `unknown` instead of `any` for untyped external data
- Prefer interfaces for object shapes; use type aliases for unions and intersections
- Use discriminated unions for state modeling (e.g., Result<T, E>)
- Derive types from schemas (Zod infer) rather than duplicating definitions

## Express

- All route handlers must be async and wrapped in error-catching middleware
- Return consistent JSON responses: `{ data: T }` on success, `{ error: string, code: string }` on failure
- Use `express.Router()` to group related routes
- Validate request bodies with Zod before processing
- Never trust `req.params` or `req.query` — parse and validate everything
- Set appropriate HTTP status codes (201 for creation, 204 for deletion)

## File Organization

- Group by feature, not by type (e.g., `src/users/` not `src/controllers/`)
- Colocate tests with source files: `foo.ts` and `foo.test.ts` in same directory
- Keep shared utilities in `src/lib/`
- One export per file for large modules; barrel exports for small utilities

## Error Handling

- Use custom error classes extending a base `AppError`
- Log errors with structured data (no plain string concatenation)
- Never swallow errors silently — always log or rethrow
